label.value: granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor complex binding

definition.value: Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the granulocyte macrophage colony-stimulating factor complex.
A protein complex that binds interleukin-12 -  comprises a beta1 and a beta2 subunit.

Regulated re-replication of DNA within a single cell cycle, resulting in an increased cell ploidy. An example of this process occurs in the synthesis of Drosophila salivary gland cell polytene chromosomes.
A membrane-bounded organelle as it is found in the host cell in which chromosomes are housed and replicated. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.
Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of any enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and orthophosphate.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with neurexins, synaptic cell surface proteins related to latrotoxin receptor, laminin and agrin. Neurexins act as cell recognition molecules at nerve terminals.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + histone -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + methyl-histone. Histone methylation generally occurs on either an arginine or lysine residue.
Providing the environmental signal that initiates the directed movement of a motile cell or organism towards a higher concentration of that signal.
Combining with a leucokinin, any of several octapeptide hormones found in insects, and transmitting the signal to initiate a change in cell activity.
The self-renewing division of a germline stem cell to produce a daughter stem cell and a daughter germ cell, which will divide to form the gametes.
Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group to an acceptor molecule -  dependent on the presence of 5,10-methylenetetrahydrofolate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group to an acceptor molecule -  dependent on the presence of 5-methyltetrahydrofolate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group to an acceptor molecule -  dependent on the presence of 5-methyltetrahydropteroyltri-L-glutamate.
Catalysis of the transfer of a methyl group to an acceptor molecule, dependent on the presence of 5-methyl-5,6,7,8-tetrahydromethanopterin.
The expansion of a T cell population by cell division. Follows T cell activation.
The expansion of a B cell population by cell division. Follows B cell activation.

A protein complex that contains a disulfide-linked heterodimer of T cell receptor (TCR) chains, which are members of the immunoglobulin superfamily, and mediates antigen recognition, ultimately resulting in T cell activation. The TCR heterodimer is associated with the CD3 complex, which consists of the nonpolymorphic polypeptides gamma, delta, epsilon, zeta, and, in some cases, eta (an RNA splice variant of zeta) or Fc epsilon chains.

label.value: positive regulation of T cell proliferation

definition.value: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of T cell proliferation.

label.value: positive regulation of T cell homeostatic proliferation

definition.value: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of resting T cell proliferation.

label.value: positive regulation of activated T cell proliferation

definition.value: Any process that activates or increases the rate or extent of activated T cell proliferation.

A T cell receptor complex in which the TCR heterodimer comprises alpha and beta chains, associated with the CD3 complex -  recognizes a complex consisting of an antigen-derived peptide bound to a class I or class II MHC protein.

A T cell receptor complex in which the TCR heterodimer comprises gamma and delta chains, associated with the CD3 complex -  recognizes antigen directly, without a requirement for processing and presentation by an MHC protein.
Catalysis of the splitting and linkage of glucan molecules, resulting in glucan chain elongation.
Catalysis of the splitting and linkage of (1--gt-3)-beta-D-glucan molecules, resulting in (1--gt-3)-beta-D-glucan chain elongation.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of cell proliferation.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of T cell proliferation.

label.value: negative regulation of T cell proliferation

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents or reduces the rate or extent of T cell proliferation.
Catalysis of the hydrolysis of thiamine phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  D-fructose 1,6-bisphosphate + H2O -eq- D-fructose 6-phosphate + phosphate.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with an unprocessed ribosomal RNA transcript.
The cell cycle process in which double-strand breaks are generated at defined hotspots throughout the genome during meiosis I. This results in the initiation of meiotic recombination.

During meiosis, the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of strand exchange proteins (recombinases) to form small, electron dense structures in association with meiotic chromosomes during leptotene and zygotene.

During meiosis, the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of strand exchange proteins (recombinases) to form small, electron dense structures in association with meiotic chromosomes during pachytene. Involved in the catalysis crossing over.

An organelle found in cnidoblast (nematoblast) cells. When matured, these stinging organelles store toxins and can deliver them when the cnidocil (a short extension of the cnidocyst) is stimulated by a prey or another stimulus.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a telomere, a specific structure at the end of a linear chromosome required for the integrity and maintenance of the end.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with the beta subunit of interleukin-12.
